<TEXT>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="11"> Language:</s>
<F>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="12"> English</s>
</F>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="13"> Article Type:BFN [Text] Yichang, February 27 (XINHUA) -- The construction of China's largest water conservancy scheme, the Three Gorges Project, has boosted real estate development in the project area.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="14"> Both domestic and overseas real estate investors are optimistic about the prospects for and potential of the real estate market there.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="15"> Yichang, the city in Central China's Hubei Province, next to the project, had 156 real estate development companies by the end of 1993.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="16"> Some 890,000 sq m of houses were built last year, 2.3 times more than in the previous year.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="17"> Of the real estate firms set up in Yichang, 30 are Sino-foreign companies which have imported funds amounting to one billion yuan (about 90 million U.S. dollars).</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="18"> The city now has 329 construction companies with over 40,000 workers building houses.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="19"> The Chinese Government plans to invest five billion yuan (about 510 million U.S. dollars) in the Three Gorges project, which is scheduled to take 17 years to complete.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="20"> Yichang has an ambitious plan to turn this medium-sized city into a big one along the Chang Jiang River by the end of the century.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="21"> It has stepped up infrastructure and real estate progress, according to Liu Xuhui, head of the city construction committee.</s>

<s docid="FBIS3-3877" num="22"> It plans to carry out an upgrading project on 67 ha of old urban areas, and build a number of residential areas, holiday villages and six million sq m of new houses in the next three years, Liu said.</s>
